'''Richard Alan John Asher''', [[Royal College of Physicians|FRCP]] (3 April 1912, [[Brighton]] &ndash; 25 April 1969, [[Marylebone]]) was an eminent [[United Kingdom|British]] [[endocrinologist]] and [[haematologist]].<ref name="Rowat2001" /> As the senior physician responsible for the mental observation ward at the [[Central Middlesex Hospital]]<ref name="BMJObituary">{{cite journal | author= Anonymous | title = R. A. J. Asher (Obituary notice) | journal = British Medical Journal | volume = 2 |issue=5653| pages = 388–388 | date = 1969-05-10 | doi= 10.1136/bmj.2.665.388 |pmc=1983233}}</ref> he described and named [[Munchausen syndrome]] in a 1951 article in ''[[The Lancet]]''.<ref name="pmid14805062">{{cite journal |author=Asher R |title=Munchausen's syndrome |journal=Lancet |volume=1 |issue=6650 |pages=339–41 |year=1951 |pmid=14805062 |doi=}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Richard Asher was born to the Reverend Felix Asher and his wife Louise (née Stern). He married [[Margaret Eliot|Margaret Augusta Eliot]] at St Pancras' Church, London on 27 July 1943,<ref>GRO Register of Marriages: September 1943 1b 4 Pancras - Asher = Eliot</ref> whereupon his father-in-law gave him a complete set of the ''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'', which physician and medical ethicist [[Maurice Henry Pappworth|Maurice Pappworth]] alleged was the source of Asher's "accidental" reputation as a medical [[Etymology|etymologist]].<ref>{{cite journal | last = Lock | first = Stephen | title = The words of medicine, R. Fortuine (book review) | journal = Med Hist | volume = 47 | issue=1 | pages = 139 | year = 2003 | pmc=1044791}} <!--No PMID--></ref> They had three children: [[Peter Asher]] (born 1944), a member of the pop duo [[Peter & Gordon]] and later record producer, [[Jane Asher]] (born 1946), a film and TV actress and novelist, and Clare Asher (born 1948), a radio actress.

The Asher family home above his private consulting rooms at 57 [[Wimpole Street]] was briefly notable when [[Paul McCartney]] lived there in 1964-1966 during his relationship with Jane Asher.<ref>{{cite book  | first = Graham | last = Vickers | title = Rock Music Landmarks of London | year = 2001 | publisher = Omnibus Press | isbn = 0-7119-8675-4 | url=http://books.google.com/?id=ZYU3euLYMAgC}}</ref>

In 1964 Asher suddenly gave up his hospital post and perhaps all medical activities.<ref name="BMJObituary" /> He suffered from depression in later life and reportedly died by his own hand at the age of 57.<ref name="Rowat2001" />

==Ideas and reputation==
Asher was regarded as "one of the foremost medical thinkers of our times",<ref name="Drew1973">
{{cite journal | last = Drew | first = Robert | title = Richard Asher Talking Sense by Francis Avery Jones (review) | journal = Proc R Soc Med |  volume = 66 | issue = 5 | pages = 488 |  year = 1973|pmc=1644921}}</ref> who emphasised the need "to be increasingly critical of our own and other people's thinking".<ref>{{cite journal | last = Asher | first = Richard | title = Straight and Crooked Thinking | journal = Br Med J | volume = 2 | issue=4885 | pages = 460–462 | year = 1954 | doi = 10.1136/bmj.2.4885.460 | pmid = 13182247 | pmc = 2078909}}</ref> Asher was particularly concerned that "many clinical notions are accepted because they are comforting rather than because there is any evidence to support them".<ref>''Talking Sense'' quoted in {{cite journal | title = Endpiece | journal = Br Medical J | volume = 2 | issue=4885 | pages = 1532 | year = 1999|pmc=1115904 | pmid=10356012 | author=Asher R}}</ref>

Asher was hailed as a pioneer<ref>{{cite journal|author= Sharpe M, Wessely S | title = Putting the rest cure to rest--again | journal = BMJ | volume = 316 | pages = 796–800 | year = 1998 | pmid=9549447 | url = http://www.bmj.com/cgi/content/full/316/7134/796|issue= 7134|pmc= 1112768|doi= 10.1136/bmj.316.7134.796}}</ref> in challenging the value of excessive bed rest following treatment,<ref>{{cite journal | last = Asher   | first = Richard | title = Dangers of Going to Bed | journal = Br Med J | volume = 2|issue=4536 | pages = 967–968 | year = 1947 | doi = 10.1136/bmj.2.4536.967 | pmc=2056244 | pmid=18897489}}</ref> and argued that the [[Pel-Ebstein fever]] (a fever characteristic for [[Hodgkin's disease]]) was an example of a condition that exists only because it has a name.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Hilson AJW, DiNubile MJ | title = Pel-Ebstein fever | journal = N Engl J Med | volume = 333 | pages = 66–67 | year = 1995 | pmid=7777006 | doi = 10.1056/NEJM199507063330118 | issue = 1}} They cite Asher's lecture ''Making Sense'' (Lancet 1959;2:359)</ref> Asher's 1949 paper "Myxoedematous Madness"<ref name="pmid18148089">{{cite journal |author=Asher R |title=Myxoedematous madness |journal=Br Med J |volume=2 |issue=4627 |pages=555–562 |year=1949 |pmid=18148089 |doi=10.1136/bmj.2.4627.555 |pmc=2051123}}</ref> alerted a generation of physicians to the interaction between the brain and the thyroid gland. As a result, young and elderly psychiatric patients are now screened for thyroid malfunction.<ref>{{Cite journal
